# company_aliases.yaml — operator-curated company-name aliases for the
# rejection-detection matcher (#362). Copy this file to company_aliases.yaml
# and edit. The runtime path is gitignored.
#
# Why this exists:
#   When a recruiter / ATS sends a rejection email, the "From" display name
#   and the email body's company reference often diverge from the canonical
#   name stored in the DB's `jobs.company` column. Example: Collaborative
#   Robotics markets the product as "Cobot"; their Ashby `From:` header is
#   "Cobot Hiring Team" and the body opens "Thank you for your interest in
#   Cobot..." but the operator applied to "Collaborative Robotics".
#
#   Without an alias, the rejection-detection matcher's token-set fuzzy
#   match returns zero overlap and the email surfaces as `unmatched`. The
#   operator then has to reattribute manually every time the same alias
#   recurs.
#
# SHAPE:
#   <alias-or-display-name>: <canonical-DB-company>
#
# Both keys and values are case-insensitive at match time. Multi-word values
# are fine. Values must match the company string the operator typed when
# applying (or whatever ingest stored).
#
# The matcher hot-reloads this file on every classify-and-match cycle, so
# editing via /config/ takes effect on the next /detect-rejections cron tick.
#
# Missing file → no aliases (matcher uses pure token-set on the email's
# extracted company against jobs.company).

# Example seed — uncomment if it applies to your search:
# cobot: collaborative robotics

# Add discovered aliases below as your operator confirmation queue surfaces them.
